<title>infromed consent</title>
    <link id="light-styles" rel="stylesheet" href="Case_sheet_styles.css">
    <link id="dark-styles" rel="alternate stylesheet" title="dark" href="Case_sheet_styles_dark.css">
<script src="https://www.youtube.com/iframe_api"></script>
        <h2>EXPAND: EXPLAINING INFORMED CONSENT</h2>
        <div class="video-container">
          <iframe allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen="" referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/z2nsuMzdtJg?origin=https://www.youtube.com" title="Informed Consent by Dr. Vaibhav" frameborder="0"></iframe>
        </div>
        <p><em>(<b>Scenario:</b> An FY2 Doctor in Medicine is asked to explain the concept of informed consent to Mr. William Hasting, a 22-year-old who wants to learn about it.)</em> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=27s">Video 0:27-0:36</a>)</p>
        <h4>A. CORE CONCEPT OF INFORMED CONSENT</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Informed consent is not simply a written form to be signed; it is fundamentally a <strong>conversation</strong> or an ongoing dialogue between the doctor and the patient. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=38s">Video 0:38-0:43</a>; <a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=138s">Video 2:18-2:23</a>)</li>
          <li>The goal is to provide the patient with all the necessary information so they can make a well-informed decision about their treatment or procedure. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=150s">Video 2:30-2:39</a>)</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>B. FRAMEWORKS FOR THE CONSENT CONVERSATION</h4>
        <p>The instructor presents two mnemonics to structure the conversation:</p>
        <ul>
          <li class="grey">
            <strong>1. The "BRAIN" Mnemonic:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=73s">Video 1:13</a>) This framework covers the key points to discuss about a procedure.
            <ul>
              <li><strong>B</strong> - Benefits of the procedure. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=76s">Video 1:16</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>R</strong> - Risks of the procedure. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=77s">Video 1:17</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>A</strong> - Alternatives to the procedure. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=78s">Video 1:18</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>I</strong> - Indication of the procedure (Why is it needed?). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=79s">Video 1:19</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>N</strong> - Nature of the procedure. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=80s">Video 1:20</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>2. The "BALANCED" Mnemonic:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=83s">Video 1:23</a>) This provides a more comprehensive structure for the entire process.
            <ul>
              <li><strong>L</strong> - Listen (to the patient's concerns). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=87s">Video 1:27</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>A</strong> - Assume Presume Capacity. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=88s">Video 1:28</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>N</strong> - Nature (of the procedure). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=89s">Video 1:29</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>B</strong> - Benefits. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=85s">Video 1:25</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>A</strong> - Alternatives. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=86s">Video 1:26</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>C</strong> - Communicate Risk. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=90s">Video 1:30</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>E</strong> - Empower / Refusal power. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=91s">Video 1:31</a>)</li>
              <li style="top: 5px; left: -1px;"><strong>D</strong> - Document notes. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&amp;t=92s">Video 1:32</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h4>C. THE SEVEN PRINCIPLES OF DECISION-MAKING AND CONSENT (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=50s">Video 0:50</a>)</h4>
        <p>The instructor refers to a leaflet outlining these core principles:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Principle 1:</strong> All patients have the right to be involved in decisions about their treatment and care and be supported to make informed decisions if they are able. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=447s">Video 7:27-7:35</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Principle 2:</strong> Decision making is an ongoing process focused on meaningful dialogue: the exchange of relevant information specific to the individual patient. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=458s">Video 7:38-7:45</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Principle 3:</strong> All patients have the right to be listened to, and to be given the information they need to make a decision and the time and support they need to understand it. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=467s">Video 7:47-7:55</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Principle 4:</strong> Doctors must try to find out what matters to patients so they can share relevant information about the benefits and harms of proposed options and reasonable alternatives, including the option to take no action. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=479s">Video 7:59-8:09</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Principle 5:</strong> Doctors must start from the presumption that all adult patients have the capacity to make decisions about their treatment and care. A patient can only be judged to lack capacity to make a specific decision at a specific time, and only after assessment in line with legal requirements. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=498s">Video 8:18-8:33</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Principle 6:</strong> The choice of treatment or care for patients who lack capacity must be of overall benefit to them, and decisions should be made in consultation with those who are close to them or advocating for them. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=516s">Video 8:36-8:53</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Principle 7:</strong> Patients whose right to consent is affected by law should be supported to be involved in the decision-making process, and to exercise choice if possible. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=539s">Video 8:59-9:06</a>)</li>
        </ul>
        <h4>D. APPLICATION AND EXAMPLES</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Patient Autonomy and Empowerment:</strong> The patient has the right to make the final decision. This includes refusing the surgery, seeking a second opinion, or talking to a consultant. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=320s">Video 5:20-5:46</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Example - Knee Replacement for Chronic Arthritis:</strong> (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=118s">Video 1:58-2:12</a>)
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Benefits:</strong> Improved mobility, pain relief. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=177s">Video 2:57-3:06</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>Alternatives:</strong> Physiotherapy, long-term painkillers. The pros and cons of these alternatives (e.g., side effects of painkillers) must also be discussed. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=195s">Video 3:15-3:27</a>)</li>
              <li><strong>Communicate Risks:</strong> Discuss risks like post-operative pain or infection and their potential management (e.g., analgesia, antibiotics). (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=309s">Video 5:09-5:24</a>)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Assessing Capacity:</strong> Always assume the patient has capacity unless they show signs of confusion. If capacity is in doubt, assess if the patient can understand, retain, and weigh the information to make and communicate a decision. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=265s">Video 4:25-4:51</a>)</li>
          <li><strong>Documentation:</strong> It is crucial to document the conversation, including the information provided and the patient's final decision. (<a class="timestamp" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z2nsuMzdtJg&t=364s">Video 6:04-6:14</a>)</li>
        </ul>
